{{DISPLAYTITLE:''The Ashtray (Or the Man Who Denied Reality)''}} {{Infobox book | name = The Ashtray (Or the Man Who Denied Reality) | author = [[Errol Morris]] | image = The Ashtray (Or the Man Who Denied Reality).jpg | subject = [[Philosophy of science]], [[epistemology]] | published = 2018 ([[University of Chicago Press]]) | pages = | isbn = 9780226922683 | italic title=no }}
'''''The Ashtray (Or the Man Who Denied Reality)''''' is a book by [[Errol Morris]] in which he criticizes the philosophy of [[Thomas Kuhn]].<ref name=mm>{{cite web|title=The Ashtray: Errol Morris Reimagines Total World Philosophy in Overwhelming New Book - MovieMaker Magazine|url=https://www.moviemaker.com/archives/news/book-review-errol-morris-the-ashtray/|website=[[MovieMaker Magazine]]|accessdate=23 May 2018|date=22 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=kitcher>{{cite web|title=The Ashtray Has Landed: The Case of Morris v. Kuhn - Los Angeles Review of Books|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/the-ashtray-has-landed-the-case-of-morris-v-kuhn/|website=[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=ashtray>{{cite web|title=Errol Morris and Thomas Kuhn: “The Intentional Ashtray Throwing Incident”|url=https://aphelis.net/errol-morris-thomas-kuhn-the-intentional-ashtray-throwing-incident/|website=[[APHELIS]]|accessdate=23 May 2018}}</ref> In the book, Morris argues that Kuhn was a [[relativism|relativist]] and a philosophical [[Idealism|idealist]], contrasting his interpretation of Kuhn's views with his own [[epistemology]], drawing on [[Hilary Putnam]] and [[Saul Kripke]], which he describes as "investigative realism", based on the belief that there is an objective reality whilst rejecting [[naïve realism]]. Morris accepts that investigation of truth involves considerable effort, with no guarantee of reaching the absolute truth, and that knowledge can be attained "through reason, through observation, through investigation, through thought, through science".<ref name=miller />
In a piece for the [[Los Angeles Review of Books]], [[Philip Kitcher]] compared Morris' critique to [[Samuel Johnson]]'s [[appeal to the stone]] regarding [[George Berkeley]]'s belief in [[subjective idealism]], stating that "Morris has no interest in considering what Kuhn might have had in mind", and rejecting his characterisation of Kuhn as a relativist and an [[Irrealism (philosophy)|irrealist]].<ref name=kitcher />
==Title== In 1972, Morris met with Kuhn at [[Princeton University]]'s [[Institute for Advanced Study]], where Morris was a graduate student and Kuhn was his academic adviser, to discuss a paper Morris had written. The conversation grew increasingly heated as they disagreed regarding some fundamental ideas - specifically regarding [[James Clerk Maxwell]]'s theory of [[displacement current]], and the concept of [[Commensurability (philosophy of science)|incommensurability]] - and eventually Kuhn threw a cut glass ashtray full of cigarette butts. Following the incident Morris left Princeton. Morris uses the ashtray as a metaphor for the [[Materialism|material reality]] that Morris believes Kuhn denied, as well what Morris views as Kuhn's intolerance of dissent from his theories.<ref name=miller>{{cite web |url=https://slate.com/culture/2018/06/errol-morris-book-about-thomas-kuhn-the-ashtray-reviewed.html|title=Errol Morris Refutes It Thus |last=Miller |first=Laura |author-link=Laura Miller (writer) |date=5 June 2018|website=[[Slate (magazine)]] |access-date=5 June 2018}}</ref><ref name=mm /><ref name=kitcher /><ref name=ashtray />
